    /************************************************************************/
    /*                                              B.Noeggerath,           */
    /* fids.docu                page 7 of 8         Rel. 2.9     05.01.1990 */
    /*                                                                      */
    /* Intern Commands       ( entered in the command line )                */
    /*                                                                      */
    /************************************************************************/

    Fids intern commands:

            cd      If cd is given without an argument,
                    the environment variable HOME is taken
                    for the chdir command.

            cd $HOME...
                    If the argument include the "$HOME"
                    it will be replaced with the environment
                    variable.

            exit    like the ^C command
                    ( try it, if the ^C does'nt work !?)

            fids_alarm
                    Set time interval in seconds!
                    ( default = 59 ).

                    If you do nothing on your terminal,
                    fids does something once after that
                    interval:
                    It updates the time of day on screen,
                    it also reads the directory new, if
                    this has been changed in the last
                    interval and it will notify you, if
                    there is a mail for you.

                    Normaly you don't have to change this
                    interval time.


    Fids intern UNIX commands:

            For description of these commands you
            should read the UNIX books.

            cp      rm      chown   pwd     mail    umask
            ln      rmdir   chgrp   id      mesg    touch
            mv      mkdir   chmod   date    uname

            These commands are executed without leaving
            fids, if no options given.

            All other commands are executed by calling
            the shell.

    Shell   If you enter the command "sh", you can work
            direct with the shell.
            The Environment variable PS1 (primary promt)
            is modified by fids to [fids].(old PS1).
            So you know how often you have called the
            fids subsequently.





