    /*                                                                      */
    /* file ".fids.pf_keys"         User definitions for PF_keys            */
    /*                                                                      */
    /************************************************************************/


    /* === PF_KEYS FOR FIDS ===    (don't change the first 4 char in each line! */
    /* functions for pf_keys 1 to 9          ^M= <CR>, ^[= <ESC>, ^T= <CTRL><T> */
    .C1=cd^M^[l
    .C2=^W
    .C3=^C
    .C4=^A
    .C5=&^[l
    .C6=^Y
    .C7=cd .^M^[l
    .C8=^Tn
    .C9=^Tm
    /* Names of the functions for display in helpline     (max.8 are displayed) */
    .L1=  HOME
    .L2= BROWSE
    .L3=  EXIT
    .L4=  EDIT
    .L5=<split>
    .L6= REMOVE
    .L7=REFRESH
    .L8= sort/n
    .L9= sort/m
    /************************************************************************/


    .Cn=            Command to be executed for the corresponding PF_key.
      (n=1..9)      All allowed fids commands may be used.

        example:    cd $HOME/c^M^[l^Tt

                    The actual directory is changed to $HOME/c.
                    ^M  = <CR>      : the execute command (page 5)

                    The file ".fids.pf_keys" will be searched and
                    if found, PF_key definitions are reloaded.
                    ^[l = <ESC>l    : the load command (page 4)

                    At least the files in that directory are sorted.
                    ^Tt             : the sort command (page 3).

            The commands are executed in the same way as if they were typed
            on the keyboard.

            PF_keys 1..9 on a standard terminal : <ESC>1..9.


    .Ln=            Labels for the corresponding PF_keys to be displayed
      (n=1..9)      on screen.


